<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910906-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>910906-0022.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Banco Central:   Pretax Earnings Rose 2.2%   During First Half of 1991</HL><DATE>09/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   BCM</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)SPAIN (SP)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Banco Central, one of Spain's largest commercial banks,said pretax profit in the first half of 1991 rose 2.2% from ayear earlier.   Banco Central said consolidated profit before taxes andincluding portfolio losses tumbled 31% to 34.63 billionpesetas ($320.2 million) from 50.29 billion pesetas.</LP><TEXT>   Operating profit for its financial group rose 9.9% to63.35 billion pesetas from 57.64 billion pesetas a yearearlier. Those figures exclude portfolio trading.   The bank said financial margins rose 4.7% to 94.84 billionpesetas, with costs climbing 13% to 178.02 billion pesetasand interest income increasing 10% to 272.86 billion pesetas.Consolidated cash flow including stock trading losses fell14% to 66.54 billion pesetas from 77.28 billion pesetas, thebank said. Total assets for the financial group reached 4.8trillion pesetas while the parent bank's assets stood at 3.7trillion pesetas.   During the first half of 1991, Banco Central and BancoHispano Americano agreed to merge, forming Spain's biggestcommercial bank. Total assets are expected to reach 8.8trillion pesetas.</TEXT></DOC>